threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, Intel 80386, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib/ld-linux.so.2, for GNU/Linux 2.6.9, not stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a backdoor that masquerades its process name as '[syslogd]' to evade detection. It establishes persistence by creating a PID file at '/var/run/daemon.pid'. The malware creates two threads, listening on raw TCP and UDP sockets for commands from a C2 server. It features a remote shell capability, executing arbitrary commands via `popen` in the `remoteExec` function. It also has functionality to download and write files to 'system.conf'. The C2 communication appears to be obfuscated with a custom XOR-based encryption routine (`myDecryptFun`).
